#let images = (
  "23.1": (
    caption: [Fall colors along Blue Ridge Parkway in Virginia. The combination of several deciduous tree species (e.g., dogwood, red maple, sugar maple, and sorrel trees) produces a wide range of hues. These autumn colors result from senescence and metabolic changes in leaves triggered by shorter day lengths and cooler temperatures.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.2": (
    caption: [Programmed cell death (PCD) is a normal part of the plant life cycle that occurs in a wide range of developmental processes and responses to environmental signals and pathogens. Cells and tissues that undergo PCD are highlighted in yellow, including megaspore formation, suspensor degeneration, endosperm breakdown, aleurone layer senescence, root cap cell death, xylem tracheary element differentiation, aerenchyma formation, leaf senescence, petal senescence, hypersensitive response to pathogens, and incompatible pollen rejection.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.3": (
    caption: [Two types of programmed cell death in plants. (A) Vacuolar-type PCD, also referred to as developmental PCD, is exemplified by xylem tracheary element differentiation. Preparation for PCD as a part of cellular differentiation is mediated by hormonal signaling, but PCD is executed only in response to a cell death trigger, such as an increase in cytosolic calcium concentration. The vacuole ruptures, releasing hydrolases that degrade cellular contents. (B) Necrotic-type PCD occurs in response to pathogen attack and is associated with the hypersensitive response. This type of PCD involves chloroplast disruption, cytoplasmic shrinkage, and rapid collapse of cellular contents.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.4": (
    caption: [Autophagosome formation in plants. Autophagosome biogenesis begins with the formation of a cup-shaped double-membrane structure called a phagophore. The edges of the phagophore grow and engulf cargo (macromolecules and organelles). The edges then fuse, forming a double-membrane vesicle called the autophagosome. Some digestion occurs within the autophagosome during its transit to the vacuole. The autophagosome eventually fuses with the vacuole, forming an autophagic body. Vacuolar hydrolases then degrade the contents of the autophagic body, and the resulting metabolites are transported back to the cytosol for reuse.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.5": (
    caption: [Autophagy plays dual roles in the regulation of plant PCD. In wild-type (WT) plants, inoculation with an avirulent pathogen induces hypersensitive response-type (HR-type) PCD at the infected leaf site. Compared with the WT, the autophagy-deficient atg5 mutant showed suppressed HR-type PCD, indicating that autophagy promotes PCD in this context. However, in response to carbon starvation or natural senescence, autophagy-deficient mutants showed accelerated PCD, indicating that autophagy can also suppress premature cell death by maintaining cellular homeostasis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.6": (
    caption: [Phenotype of wild-type Arabidopsis and the autophagy-defective mutant atg4a4b-1. (A) Wild-type rosette leaves showing normal development. (B) Autophagy-defective mutant rosette leaves exhibiting accelerated senescence with yellowing and premature cell death. The balance between autophagy's dual roles enables efficient recycling of cellular components while preventing premature cell death.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.7": (
    caption: [Sequential leaf senescence of wheat stems showing a gradient of senescence from the older leaves at the base to the younger leaves near the tip. This pattern is observed in September and October, with progressive yellowing and senescence moving from bottom to top as the plant develops and ages. Sequential senescence is characteristic of monocarpic plants that die after seed production.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.8": (
    caption: [Seasonal leaf senescence in an aspen tree (Populus tremula). All of the leaves begin to senesce in late September and undergo abscission in early October. In contrast to sequential leaf senescence, the leaves of deciduous trees in temperate climates undergo seasonal synchronous senescence, triggered by environmental cues such as shorter photoperiods and cooler temperatures rather than age-dependent developmental programs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.9": (
    caption: [Ultrastructure of chloroplasts and gerontoplasts in mesophyll cells of barley leaf. Chloroplasts before senescence (A) show well-organized grana stacks and intact internal membrane structure. Gerontoplasts from leaves in which about 50% of the chlorophyll has been lost (B) show progressive unstacking of grana and the loss of internal membrane structure. During leaf senescence, chloroplasts are transformed into gerontoplasts, which lose their photosynthetic capacity but continue to carry out other metabolic processes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.10": (
    caption: [Pathways for vacuolar degradation of chloroplasts and their proteins. Chloroplasts can be selectively degraded via several different pathways. In the Rubisco-containing body (RCB) pathway, a chloroplast protrusion is sequestered by an isolation membrane to form an autophagosome specifically containing stromal proteins enclosed in a small vesicle. In the ATI pathway, small ATI vesicles bud from the chloroplast outer envelope and are delivered to the vacuole. Whole chloroplasts can also be directly delivered to the vacuole. These pathways allow selective and efficient degradation of chloroplast components during senescence.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.11": (
    caption: [Chlorophyll catabolism pathway and compartmentation during leaf senescence. Chlorophyll degradation begins in the chloroplast, where chlorophyll b is converted to chlorophyll a by chlorophyll b reductase. The phytol tail is removed by chlorophyllase, and the porphyrin ring is opened by pheophorbide a oxygenase (PAO) to form red chlorophyll catabolite (RCC). RCC is then converted to primary fluorescent chlorophyll catabolite (pFCC) in the chloroplast. pFCC is exported to the cytosol and imported into the vacuole, where it is converted to nonfluorescent chlorophyll catabolites (NCCs) and stored. This pathway prevents the accumulation of phototoxic intermediates.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.12": (
    caption: [Metabolic pathways that are either up-regulated or down-regulated during senescence in Arabidopsis. Down-regulated pathways (shown in blue) include photosynthesis, carbon fixation, and anabolism. Up-regulated pathways (shown in red) include degradation processes, nutrient remobilization, hormone signaling (ABA, jasmonic acid, ethylene), and stress responses. This coordinated regulation ensures efficient nutrient recycling while preventing premature cell death.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.13": (
    caption: [Overview of the signaling pathways and regulatory networks involved in leaf senescence. Leaf senescence is finely regulated at multiple levels: chromatin structure through histone modifiers such as HDA9, HLS1, and SUVH2; transcription through transcription factors including NAC, WRKY, and MYB families; posttranscription through microRNAs and RNA-binding proteins; translation through selective mRNA translation; and posttranslation through protein modifications. This multi-layered regulation allows precise temporal control of senescence in response to developmental and environmental signals.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.14": (
    caption: [Regulation of leaf senescence in Arabidopsis by a trifurcate feed-forward pathway involving EIN2, miR164, and ORE1. ORE1 promotes leaf senescence, and its expression is induced in an age-dependent manner by EIN2. ORE1 is negatively regulated at the posttranscriptional level by miR164 at earlier stages of leaf life; this repression is alleviated as the leaf ages and miR164 levels decline. EIN2 also directly suppresses miR164 expression, creating a coherent feed-forward loop that ensures robust activation of senescence at the appropriate developmental stage.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.15": (
    caption: [Multi-layered regulation of leaf senescence by WRKY53. Up-regulation of WRKY53 expression during leaf senescence is partially regulated by SUVH2-mediated histone methylation at the chromatin level. WRKY53 recruits HDA9 and PWR to its target sites, which facilitates histone deacetylation by HDA9 and suppresses the expression of associated genes, including negative regulators of senescence. WRKY53 is also regulated by posttranscriptional mechanisms involving microRNAs and by protein-protein interactions that modulate its activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.16": (
    caption: [The regulatory network that induces leaf senescence in response to extended darkness. In sufficient light (high R:FR ratio), PIFs are degraded through a phytochrome B (phyB)–dependent mechanism, thus suppressing PIF-dependent activation of senescence. In deep shade and darkness (low R:FR), phyB-mediated PIF degradation is inhibited, allowing PIFs to accumulate and activate senescence-associated genes including ORE1 and other senescence-promoting transcription factors. This light-quality sensing mechanism allows plants to initiate senescence when light conditions become unfavorable.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.17": (
    caption: [Interaction between the circadian clock and aging in Arabidopsis. (A) The senescence signal is integrated with the circadian clock through TOC1, one of the core oscillators, resulting in shortening of the circadian period with leaf age. (B) The expression of CCA1, another component of the circadian clock, shows altered amplitude and phase with increasing leaf age. This clock-aging interaction allows plants to coordinate senescence with daily rhythms and ensures that senescence-related processes occur at optimal times of day.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.18": (
    caption: [Cytokinin is a negative regulator of leaf senescence in transgenic tobacco. (A) To generate the construct used in this experiment, a senescence-induced promoter was fused to a cytokinin biosynthesis gene, ipt, from Agrobacterium tumefaciens. At the onset of senescence of transgenic plants carrying this construct, the promoter drives ipt expression, leading to cytokinin accumulation. (B) Control untransformed plants show normal age-dependent senescence. (C) Transgenic plants with the senescence-induced cytokinin production show delayed senescence and remain green longer, demonstrating that cytokinins actively suppress senescence progression.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.19": (
    caption: [Abscission zone and associated tissues. (A) Light micrograph of the abscission zone at the base of a leaf of the maidenhair tree (Ginkgo biloba), showing specialized small cells with thin cell walls. (B) Diagram of the cells of the abscission zone, showing the separation layer (dark green) where cell wall degradation occurs. (C) As the cell walls in the separation layer are broken down by hydrolytic enzymes, the cells separate from each other. (D) Scanning electron micrograph showing the detailed structure of separated cells after abscission.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.20": (
    caption: [Effect of ethylene on abscission in the birch Betula pendula. The tree on the left is the wild type showing normal autumn leaf abscission. The tree on the right was transformed with a mutated version of the Arabidopsis ethylene receptor gene, ETR1, which confers ethylene insensitivity. The expression of this gene prevents normal abscission, and the tree retains its leaves well into winter, demonstrating the essential role of ethylene perception in the abscission process.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.21": (
    caption: [Schematic view of the roles of auxin and ethylene during leaf abscission. In the abscission induction phase, the level of auxin decreases in the leaf blade and petiole, while the level of ethylene increases. These changes in the hormonal balance increase the sensitivity of the target cells in the abscission zone to ethylene. In the abscission execution phase, ethylene signaling activates cell wall-degrading enzymes in the separation layer, leading to cell wall breakdown and organ separation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.22": (
    caption: [Model for cellular signaling during abscission. (A) During abscission, specialized cells in the abscission zone capable of undergoing programmed cell separation respond to reduced levels of auxin from the leaf blade and augmented levels of ethylene to become competent to respond to abscission signals. (B) Ethylene signaling activates transcription factors that induce expression of cell wall-degrading enzymes such as cellulases, polygalacturonases, and pectinases. These enzymes degrade the middle lamella and primary cell walls in the separation layer, resulting in cell separation and organ abscission.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.23": (
    caption: [Monocarpic senescence in soybean (Glycine max). The entire plant on the left underwent senescence after flowering and producing fruit (pods), demonstrating typical monocarpic senescence where the whole plant dies after reproduction. The plant on the right remained green and vegetative because its flowers were continually removed, preventing reproduction-induced senescence. This demonstrates that monocarpic senescence is triggered by reproductive development rather than being age-dependent.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.24": (
    caption: [Century plant (Agave americana) flowers after 10–30 years of vegetative growth, after which it undergoes monocarpic senescence. This dramatic example of monocarpic senescence shows that some plants can maintain vegetative growth for extended periods before a single reproductive event triggers whole-plant senescence and death. The plant produces a tall flowering stalk that can reach several meters in height.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.25": (
    caption: [Annual growth in height of eucalyptus and sequoia trees as a function of the beginning height of the tree in the year 2006. In both cases, the growth in height declined with tree height, showing a negative correlation between tree size and growth rate. This pattern illustrates aspects of polycarpic senescence in long-lived perennial plants, where growth rates decline with age and size even though the plants continue to reproduce.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23.26": (
    caption: [Aboveground mass growth rates for 110,153 trees belonging to 89 species in North America. Trunk diameters (cm) are shown on the upper horizontal axis; the aboveground tree mass, expressed as log10 (mass in Mg [megagrams]), is shown on the lower horizontal axis; the mass growth rate (Mg yr–1) is shown on the vertical axis. The data show that mass growth rate generally increases with tree size, even though height growth declines. This indicates that large old trees continue to accumulate biomass at high rates despite declining height growth.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-23.1": (
    caption: [Longevity of various individual and perennial clonal plants. Individual plants show a wide range of lifespans, from hundreds to thousands of years for species like bristlecone pine (up to 4,600 years) and giant sequoia (up to 3,200 years). Perennial clonal plants can persist even longer through vegetative reproduction, with some clones potentially living for tens of thousands of years. This table illustrates the tremendous variation in plant lifespan and the factors that contribute to polycarpic senescence patterns.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
)
